window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.reading = CISA.reading || {};
CISA.reading[3] = [{"heading":"Project Governance and Management","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>Domain 3 — Information Systems Acquisition, Development, and Implementation</span> is roughly 12% of the CISA exam, and almost every item is written from one seat: the <span class='keyterm'>independent IS auditor</span>. You are never asked to code, choose an architecture, or run the project. You are asked to evaluate whether the acquisition or development effort is <em>governed</em>, whether risk is being managed, and whether adequate controls are being designed into the system as it is built rather than bolted on afterward. The exam repeatedly rewards the answer that reflects independence, evidence, and a control mindset over the answer that reflects technical enthusiasm. Hold that frame through every section.</p><p>Project governance is the structure that keeps an IT project aligned with the business objectives that justified it. The single most tested governance body is the <span class='keyterm'>steering committee</span> (sometimes called an IT steering committee or project board). It is composed of senior representatives from the business units affected, IT, and often finance, and it exists to <em>approve, prioritize, fund, and monitor</em> projects — not to perform day-to-day management. When an exam item asks who is ultimately responsible for a project's success or who should resolve a dispute over scope or budget, the steering committee is usually the best answer, because success is a business outcome, not a technical one. The auditor evaluates whether the committee exists, meets, has documented terms of reference, includes the right business membership, and actually reviews project status against the business case.</p><h3>Roles, Responsibilities, and the Sponsor</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>project sponsor</span> is the senior business owner who champions the project, owns the business case, secures funding, and is accountable for realizing benefits. The sponsor typically comes from the primary user department — <em>not</em> from IT — because the project exists to serve a business need. The <span class='keyterm'>project manager (PM)</span> is responsible for day-to-day delivery: planning, scheduling, resource coordination, and reporting. The PM manages the triple constraint but does not own scope decisions; material scope changes belong to the sponsor and steering committee. <span class='keyterm'>User (business) management</span> defines requirements, supplies acceptance criteria, performs user acceptance testing, and ultimately signs off. <span class='keyterm'>Senior management</span> provides the overall mandate and resources. The auditor's recurring concern is <em>segregation and clarity</em>: are roles documented, is there a single accountable sponsor, and is the user community genuinely engaged rather than a passive recipient of whatever IT delivers? Lack of user involvement is one of the most cited root causes of project failure and a frequent exam theme.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Primary responsibility</th><th>What the auditor verifies</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Steering committee</td><td>Approve, prioritize, fund, monitor; align to strategy</td><td>Charter, membership, minutes, decisions tied to business case</td></tr><tr><td>Project sponsor</td><td>Owns business case and benefits; from the business, not IT</td><td>Named, senior, accountable, present at reviews</td></tr><tr><td>Project manager</td><td>Day-to-day delivery: scope, schedule, cost, reporting</td><td>Plan, status reports, issue/risk logs, change control</td></tr><tr><td>User management</td><td>Requirements, acceptance criteria, UAT, sign-off</td><td>Documented involvement and formal approvals</td></tr><tr><td>Quality assurance</td><td>Independent review of process and deliverables</td><td>QA separate from development; reviews evidenced</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The Triple Constraint and the Project Charter</h3><p>Every project balances the <span class='keyterm'>triple constraint</span>: scope, time, and cost, bounded by an expected level of quality. Change one and at least one other must move. The exam expects you to recognize that uncontrolled expansion of scope — <span class='keyterm'>scope creep</span> — is the classic driver of overruns, and the control against it is a formal <span class='keyterm'>change control process</span> in which every proposed change is documented, assessed for impact on schedule and cost, approved by the appropriate authority, and re-baselined. The auditor looks for a <span class='keyterm'>project charter</span> that authorizes the project, names the sponsor and PM, states objectives, and sets the initial scope, budget, and high-level schedule. Without a charter, there is no baseline against which to measure whether the project is on track — and no authority for the PM to draw on organizational resources.</p><h3>Project Estimation and Scheduling Techniques</h3><p>CISA expects familiarity with the classic estimation and scheduling tools, again from the standpoint of what they let the auditor evaluate. <span class='keyterm'>Function Point Analysis (FPA)</span> sizes a system by counting its external inputs, outputs, inquiries, internal logical files, and external interface files, weighting each for complexity. Because it measures functionality delivered to the user rather than lines of code, FPA is language-independent and useful for estimating effort and for productivity comparison; the auditor may use it to sanity-check whether an estimate was derived methodically or simply guessed. A <span class='keyterm'>Gantt chart</span> is a horizontal bar chart that shows tasks against a calendar and is excellent for depicting status and simple dependencies, but it does not clearly reveal which activities determine the overall finish date.</p><p>For that you need network techniques. <span class='keyterm'>PERT (Program Evaluation and Review Technique)</span> models each activity with three time estimates — optimistic, most likely, and pessimistic — and computes a weighted expected duration ((optimistic + 4×most-likely + pessimistic) ÷ 6), which makes it suited to projects with high uncertainty. <span class='keyterm'>CPM (Critical Path Method)</span> identifies the <span class='keyterm'>critical path</span>: the longest sequence of dependent activities through the network, which determines the shortest possible project duration. Any activity on the critical path has zero <span class='keyterm'>float (slack)</span>, so a one-day slip there slips the whole project, whereas an activity off the critical path can absorb some delay. When an exam item asks which activities a PM should watch most closely, or where compressing the schedule (crashing or fast-tracking) will actually shorten delivery, the answer is the critical path. A related control technique is <span class='keyterm'>timeboxing</span> — fixing a hard delivery date and adjusting scope to fit — which is common in agile and rapid-development approaches and is a useful defense against endless slippage, at the cost of deferring lower-priority features.</p><p><span class='keyterm'>Earned Value Management (EVM)</span> lets the auditor and PM measure progress objectively by comparing three quantities: planned value (budgeted cost of work scheduled), earned value (budgeted cost of work actually performed), and actual cost. From these come the schedule variance and cost variance, and the SPI and CPI indices. An index below 1.0 signals the project is behind schedule or over budget. EVM matters to the auditor because it substitutes measured evidence for the optimistic self-assessment (\"we're about 90% done\") that so often masks a troubled project.</p><p>The auditor should also recognize where these techniques belong and their limits. A Gantt chart communicates schedule and status well to stakeholders but hides the dependency logic that determines the finish date; PERT and CPM expose that logic but demand a well-defined activity network to be meaningful. FPA sizes functionality but says nothing about technical difficulty or team productivity on its own. EVM requires a credible baseline and honest measurement of work completed — if the percent-complete figures are inflated, the indices simply give the optimism a numeric veneer. The auditor's interest is therefore less in which tool was chosen than in whether the project has an objective, evidence-based way to know where it stands, and whether that information reaches the steering committee in time to act. A project that reports only narrative status, with no baseline and no measured progress, denies management the very evidence governance depends on.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>When a question asks who is <b>ultimately responsible</b> for a project or who resolves cross-functional conflict, favor the <b>steering committee / sponsor (business)</b> over the project manager or IT. When it asks which activities most affect the completion date, the answer is the <b>critical path</b>. When it asks how to control scope, the answer is a <b>formal change-control process</b>, not \"work harder.\"</p></div><h3>Risk Management Within the Project</h3><p>A well-run project maintains a living <span class='keyterm'>risk register</span> and <span class='keyterm'>issue log</span>: risks are identified, rated by likelihood and impact, assigned owners, and given response strategies (avoid, mitigate, transfer, accept). The auditor evaluates whether risk management is continuous rather than a one-time formality, whether risks are escalated to the steering committee when they exceed the PM's tolerance, and whether the project's own risks (schedule, resource, technical, vendor) are distinguished from the operational risks that the new system will introduce once live. A frequent audit finding is a risk register created at kickoff and never updated. The auditor also checks that <span class='keyterm'>quality assurance</span> is independent of the development team, that <span class='keyterm'>project post-mortems (lessons learned)</span> are captured, and — crucially for independence — that if IS auditors participate during development as advisors, they do so in a way that does not later compromise their objectivity when the system is audited in production. Advising on control design is acceptable; making management decisions is not.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor reviews a large ERP implementation and finds the steering committee has not met in four months, status reports show \"green\" across the board, but three milestones have already slipped and the risk register is unchanged since kickoff. The <b>most significant</b> concern is not the slipped dates themselves but the <b>breakdown of governance and monitoring</b>: without an active steering committee and current risk information, management lacks the evidence to make funding and scope decisions, and \"green\" status is unsupported. The auditor's recommendation targets restoring governance oversight and objective status reporting (e.g., earned-value or milestone evidence), not day-to-day task management.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Business Case and Feasibility Analysis","body":"<p>Before an organization commits money to build or buy a system, it should justify the investment and confirm that the proposed solution is realistic. Two artifacts carry that burden: the <span class='keyterm'>feasibility study</span>, which asks <em>can we and should we do this at all</em>, and the <span class='keyterm'>business case</span>, which asks <em>is this the right investment and what value will it return</em>. The IS auditor's role is to evaluate whether these documents exist, whether they were prepared with rigor and reasonable assumptions, whether they were approved by the appropriate authority (typically the steering committee), and — critically — whether the business case is treated as a <em>living</em> document that is revisited at each major decision point rather than filed and forgotten. A project that no longer satisfies its business case should be re-justified or stopped; the auditor looks for that discipline.</p><h3>The Four Dimensions of Feasibility</h3><p>A complete feasibility study examines several distinct dimensions, and the exam expects you to distinguish them. <span class='keyterm'>Technical feasibility</span> asks whether the technology, skills, and infrastructure exist to build and operate the solution — can it actually be done with available or obtainable capability. <span class='keyterm'>Economic feasibility</span> asks whether the benefits justify the costs; this is where cost-benefit analysis lives and is the most heavily tested dimension. <span class='keyterm'>Operational feasibility</span> asks whether the organization and its people will actually use and support the system — does it fit existing processes, will users accept it, can operations run it. <span class='keyterm'>Schedule (time) feasibility</span> asks whether the solution can be delivered within a useful timeframe. Some frameworks add <span class='keyterm'>legal/regulatory feasibility</span> (can we do this within law and contract) and <span class='keyterm'>behavioral feasibility</span> (human and cultural acceptance). A recurring exam pattern gives a scenario and asks which type of feasibility a stated concern belongs to: a worry that staff will resist the new workflow is <em>operational/behavioral</em>; a worry that the required real-time throughput exceeds current hardware is <em>technical</em>; a worry that the payback period is too long is <em>economic</em>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Feasibility type</th><th>Core question</th><th>Example concern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Technical</td><td>Can it be built and run with available capability?</td><td>Throughput exceeds current infrastructure</td></tr><tr><td>Economic</td><td>Do benefits justify costs?</td><td>Payback period is too long; negative NPV</td></tr><tr><td>Operational</td><td>Will the organization use and support it?</td><td>Users resist the new process; ops can't maintain it</td></tr><tr><td>Schedule</td><td>Can it be delivered in time to matter?</td><td>Delivery slips past the regulatory deadline</td></tr><tr><td>Legal/regulatory</td><td>Is it permissible under law and contract?</td><td>Data handling conflicts with privacy law</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Cost-Benefit Analysis and Investment Metrics</h3><p>Economic feasibility rests on a disciplined <span class='keyterm'>cost-benefit analysis (CBA)</span> that enumerates all costs and all benefits over the system's life, distinguishing <span class='keyterm'>tangible</span> from <span class='keyterm'>intangible</span> items. Tangible costs include hardware, software licenses, development labor, migration, training, and ongoing maintenance and operations; the auditor is alert to <span class='keyterm'>total cost of ownership (TCO)</span>, because organizations chronically underestimate recurring operational and maintenance cost and overstate one-time savings. Tangible benefits (reduced headcount, lower error rates, faster cycle time) can be quantified; intangible benefits (improved customer satisfaction, better decision support, regulatory goodwill) are real but harder to measure and must not be inflated to make a weak case look strong. The auditor's job is not to redo management's math but to assess whether the assumptions are reasonable, sourced, and not biased toward approval.</p><p>A recurring audit concern is <em>optimism bias</em> in the analysis: the natural tendency of a project's advocates to overstate benefits, understate costs, and compress timelines to win approval. The auditor's defenses are to check that costs include the full life cycle (not just build cost), that benefits are supported by evidence rather than assertion, that a realistic range or sensitivity analysis is presented rather than a single rosy point estimate, and that the do-nothing baseline and at least one genuine alternative were considered so the recommended option was actually chosen on merit. Where benefits are speculative, the analysis should say so rather than dress intangibles up as hard savings. The auditor also confirms the analysis was reviewed and challenged by someone other than its author — ideally the steering committee — before funding was committed, since an unchallenged business case is where wishful thinking hides.</p><p>Several investment metrics recur on the exam, and you should know what each measures and its main limitation:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Return on Investment (ROI)</span> — net benefit divided by cost, expressed as a percentage. Simple and intuitive, but by itself ignores the timing of cash flows.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Payback period</span> — how long until cumulative benefits recover the initial investment. Easy to grasp and useful as a risk screen (shorter is less risky), but it ignores everything after payback and ignores the time value of money.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Net Present Value (NPV)</span> — discounts all future cash flows to today's dollars using a discount rate and sums them. A <em>positive</em> NPV means the investment adds value; NPV is generally the most rigorous single metric because it accounts for the time value of money and the full life of the investment.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Internal Rate of Return (IRR)</span> — the discount rate at which NPV equals zero; compared against the organization's required rate (hurdle rate). Higher IRR is more attractive, but IRR can mislead when comparing projects of very different size or with unusual cash-flow patterns.</li></ul><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>If a question asks which technique best accounts for the <b>time value of money</b> or gives the most complete picture of an investment's worth, choose <b>NPV</b> (or IRR). <b>Payback period</b> is the choice when the concern is <b>how quickly the investment is recovered / liquidity risk</b>. Do not choose payback or simple ROI as \"most rigorous\" — they ignore discounting.</p></div><h3>The Business Case as a Control</h3><p>The business case is more than a funding pitch; the auditor treats it as a <span class='keyterm'>control artifact</span>. A sound business case states the business problem or opportunity, the options considered (including the do-nothing baseline and buy-versus-build), the recommended option with its costs, benefits, risks, and assumptions, and the criteria and timeline for measuring success. The exam stresses that the business case must be <span class='keyterm'>revisited at key milestones</span> — sometimes called stage gates or phase-gate reviews. At each gate the steering committee re-confirms that the case still holds before releasing the next tranche of funding. If costs have ballooned or the expected benefit has evaporated, the disciplined outcome is to re-scope or cancel. An auditor who finds a project running purely on momentum, with no one checking it against the original justification, has found a genuine governance weakness — the classic \"throwing good money after bad\" (sunk-cost) failure.</p><p>The exam draws a subtle but important line between the feasibility study and the business case, and between both and the project charter. The feasibility study is analytical and comes first: it tests whether the options are viable across the technical, economic, operational, and schedule dimensions and narrows the field. The business case builds on it to make the investment argument for the recommended option and to define the benefits and success criteria against which the project will later be judged. The charter (Section 1) then authorizes the chosen project and gives the manager a mandate. An auditor who finds a project that leapt straight to procurement or coding with no documented feasibility analysis or approved business case has found a governance gap regardless of how the project ultimately turns out, because the organization committed resources without demonstrating the investment was justified or the solution viable — and without a baseline of promised benefits to hold anyone to.</p><h3>Benefits Realization</h3><p>Approval based on projected benefits means little if no one later verifies the benefits actually materialized. <span class='keyterm'>Benefits realization</span> is the discipline of defining measurable benefits up front, assigning ownership for delivering them (usually the sponsor), and measuring actual outcomes after go-live — typically as part of the post-implementation review. The auditor checks that benefits were expressed in measurable terms with a baseline, that responsibility for realizing them was assigned, and that a process exists to compare projected to actual results and to feed lessons back into future investment decisions. Because benefits often accrue over months or years, benefits realization frequently spans beyond the project's formal close, which is why it links tightly to Section 8's post-implementation review.</p><p>From an audit standpoint, benefits realization is what converts the business case from a one-time sales document into an accountability mechanism. Without it, an organization can approve investment after investment on the strength of projected returns that no one ever verifies, so poor estimating is never corrected and weak projects are never stopped. The auditor therefore looks for a closed loop: benefits defined measurably with a baseline at approval, a named owner responsible for delivering them, a scheduled measurement of actual results after go-live, and — critically — a governance forum that reviews the comparison and acts on shortfalls. Finding that benefits were promised to secure funding but were never measured afterward is a genuine control weakness, because it means the organization's investment decisions run open-loop, informed by hope rather than evidence.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor reviews a completed system-selection decision and finds the business case quantified only development cost and projected first-year labor savings, omitting multi-year maintenance, licensing renewals, and training. The <b>most appropriate</b> finding is that the economic analysis understated <b>total cost of ownership</b>, biasing the decision toward approval; the auditor recommends that future business cases use full life-cycle costing and be re-validated at stage gates, and that projected benefits be defined measurably so realization can be confirmed after go-live.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"System Development Methodologies","body":"<p>Whether an organization buys a package or builds custom software, it should follow a defined, repeatable process. The <span class='keyterm'>Systems Development Life Cycle (SDLC)</span> is the exam's backbone model, and the auditor's interest is twofold: that a disciplined methodology is followed at all, and that <em>controls, security, and audit involvement are built into each phase</em> rather than tacked on at the end. Building controls in from requirements is far cheaper and more effective than retrofitting them, and this \"shift-left\" principle underlies many correct answers.</p><h3>The Traditional (Waterfall) SDLC Phases</h3><p>The classic <span class='keyterm'>waterfall</span> model proceeds through sequential phases, each producing deliverables that are reviewed and approved before the next begins:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Feasibility / initiation</span> — justify the project (see Section 2); produce the feasibility study and business case.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Requirements definition</span> — capture what the system must do, in business terms, with measurable acceptance criteria. The auditor cares deeply here: requirements are where <em>control requirements</em> (input validation, audit trails, segregation of duties, retention) should be specified. Errors introduced in requirements are the costliest to fix later.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Design</span> — translate requirements into a technical design (architecture, data model, interfaces, and the specific application controls). Detailed design specifies the check digits, reconciliations, and error handling that will enforce data integrity.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Development / build</span> — write and unit-test code following coding standards; enforce version control and separation of the development environment from test and production.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Testing</span> — unit, integration, system, and user acceptance testing against the documented requirements (covered in Section 5).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Implementation / deployment</span> — migrate data, cut over, and place the system in production (Sections 6 and 7).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Post-implementation and maintenance</span> — review success and then maintain the system through controlled changes (Section 8).</li></ul><p>Waterfall's strengths are discipline, clear documentation, and well-defined sign-off gates, which make it easy to audit and well suited to stable, well-understood requirements (and to regulated environments). Its weakness is rigidity: because working software appears only late, requirements misunderstandings can go undetected until testing, when correction is expensive. The exam expects you to know that the <em>cost of correcting an error rises steeply the later it is found</em> — cheapest in requirements, most expensive in production.</p><p>Whatever the model, the auditor's constant question is where the <em>control checkpoints</em> live. In waterfall those checkpoints are explicit: a phase-end review and sign-off gate the transition to the next phase, and each produces documentation the auditor can inspect. This makes waterfall easy to audit and is one reason it persists in regulated and safety-critical settings despite its rigidity. The auditor evaluates whether those gates are real approvals by the right authority — the requirements approved by the business, the design reviewed for control adequacy, the test results reviewed before deployment — or merely rubber stamps. A methodology on paper that is not actually enforced is a common finding: the process document describes gates the project skipped under schedule pressure. The auditor tests the process as performed, not as documented, by sampling deliverables and approvals for a real project.</p><p>A related concept the exam expects is the <span class='keyterm'>V-model</span>, which pairs each development phase with a corresponding test level: requirements pair with acceptance testing, system design with system testing, and detailed design/coding with unit and integration testing. The V-model makes visible the principle that the way you will <em>verify</em> a phase should be planned <em>as</em> that phase is specified — you write the acceptance criteria when you write the requirements, not after the system is built. This early planning of verification is exactly the discipline the auditor wants to see, because it forces measurable, testable requirements (including control requirements) rather than vague aspirations that cannot be objectively confirmed. Regardless of methodology, the auditor also confirms that basic engineering hygiene is present: source code under version control, coding and security standards defined and followed, peer review or code review of changes, and separation of the environments in which code is written, tested, and run.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Character</th><th>Best when</th><th>Auditor's key concern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Waterfall</td><td>Sequential, heavily documented, gated sign-offs</td><td>Requirements stable and well understood</td><td>Late discovery of errors; rigidity</td></tr><tr><td>Iterative / incremental</td><td>Repeated build-test cycles delivering increasing function</td><td>Requirements partly known, evolving</td><td>Scope and version control across iterations</td></tr><tr><td>Prototyping / RAD</td><td>Fast mock-ups refined with users; timeboxed</td><td>Requirements unclear; UI-heavy; speed needed</td><td>Weak documentation; controls/security skipped for speed</td></tr><tr><td>Spiral</td><td>Iterative with explicit risk analysis each loop</td><td>Large, high-risk projects</td><td>That risk analysis is genuine, not nominal</td></tr><tr><td>Agile</td><td>Short sprints, working software, close user collaboration</td><td>Fast-changing requirements, engaged users</td><td>Lighter documentation; embedding controls each sprint</td></tr><tr><td>DevOps</td><td>Continuous integration/delivery, automation</td><td>Frequent releases; mature automation culture</td><td>Automated gates, segregation, and change evidence</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Iterative, Incremental, and Prototyping Approaches</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Iterative and incremental</span> models break the system into portions delivered over repeated cycles, so working functionality and user feedback arrive earlier and requirements can be refined along the way. <span class='keyterm'>Prototyping</span> builds a quick, often throwaway, model to clarify unclear requirements and validate the user interface; <span class='keyterm'>Rapid Application Development (RAD)</span> combines prototyping, timeboxing, and small teams to compress delivery. The auditor's caution with all speed-oriented approaches is consistent: in the rush to deliver, <em>documentation, security, and control design are the first things skipped</em>. A prototype accepted as final without hardening, a RAD build with no design documentation, or an iterative effort with no version control are common findings. The <span class='keyterm'>spiral model</span> is essentially iterative development with an explicit <span class='keyterm'>risk analysis</span> at the start of each loop, making it suited to large, high-risk efforts — provided the risk analysis is real and not a checkbox.</p><h3>Agile and DevOps</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Agile</span> methods (Scrum, XP, Kanban) deliver working software in short <span class='keyterm'>sprints/iterations</span>, favor close collaboration with an on-team business representative (the product owner), and value responding to change over following a fixed plan. Agile is not \"no process\" and it is not \"no controls\" — a common misconception the exam probes. The auditor adapts: instead of one big sign-off gate, controls appear as the <span class='keyterm'>definition of done</span>, sprint reviews, automated testing, and the product backlog, and audit evidence comes from tools (version control history, ticket systems, CI logs) rather than thick documents. The risk to evaluate is that lighter documentation and rapid change can let control requirements and security testing slip between sprints; the auditor confirms that security and control acceptance criteria are part of the definition of done. <span class='keyterm'>DevOps</span> extends agility into operations with <span class='keyterm'>continuous integration and continuous delivery/deployment (CI/CD)</span> and heavy automation. Its control questions are automation-specific: are automated quality and security gates enforced in the pipeline, is <span class='keyterm'>separation of duties</span> preserved when developers can push to production, and does the pipeline itself produce a reliable audit trail of what was changed, tested, approved, and deployed? \"DevSecOps\" simply names the practice of embedding security controls into that automated pipeline.</p><h3>Buy Versus Build and Acquisition</h3><p>Many systems are acquired rather than built. When purchasing packaged software or engaging a service provider, the exam expects a controlled selection process: define requirements first, then issue a <span class='keyterm'>Request for Proposal (RFP)</span>, evaluate responses against weighted, predefined criteria, and select on merit rather than on a vendor relationship. The auditor evaluates whether requirements preceded vendor contact (not the reverse), whether evaluation criteria were defined <em>before</em> proposals arrived, whether references and financial viability were checked, and whether the contract addresses the right to audit, service levels, source-code <span class='keyterm'>escrow</span> (so the buyer can maintain the software if the vendor fails), data ownership, and exit provisions. <span class='keyterm'>Gap analysis</span> between requirements and package capability, plus a plan for handling gaps through configuration rather than heavy customization, is a key deliverable — excessive customization of a package undermines vendor support and future upgrades and is itself an audit concern.</p><p>Acquisition does not remove the need for the disciplines above; it relocates them. There is still a life cycle — requirements, selection (in place of build), configuration and any customization, testing, conversion, and implementation — and the auditor evaluates each. Configuration testing confirms the package, once tuned to the organization's parameters, actually meets requirements; interface testing confirms it exchanges data correctly with surrounding systems; and user acceptance testing is if anything more important, because the buyer did not design the software and must verify it fits the business. Ongoing considerations become contractual rather than internal: the auditor checks that the organization retains the right to audit the provider or obtain independent assurance (for example a SOC report), that patch and upgrade responsibilities are defined, that data portability and an exit path are secured so the organization is not locked in, and that the vendor's continued viability is monitored — the reason source-code escrow exists. The message is that \"buy\" shifts the locus of control from code you write to a contract and a relationship you must govern, and the auditor's scope follows accordingly.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>The exam does <b>not</b> reward \"agile means no controls or documentation.\" Correct answers keep control objectives constant and change only the <b>evidence and timing</b>: sprint reviews, definition of done, automated tests, and tool-based audit trails. For acquisition, the recurring right answer is <b>define requirements before selecting a vendor</b> and evaluate against <b>predefined criteria</b>.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>Developers adopt a CI/CD pipeline and now deploy to production several times a day; a developer can commit code and trigger the deployment. Asked for the <b>greatest</b> control concern, the auditor identifies the loss of <b>segregation of duties</b> between development and production release. The recommended control is not to abandon CI/CD but to enforce it through the pipeline: mandatory peer code review, automated security and quality gates, an independent approval step before production promotion, and immutable pipeline logs providing the audit trail.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Control Identification and Design","body":"<p>This section is the heart of Domain 3 for an IS auditor. Controls are cheapest and most effective when <em>designed into the system during requirements and design</em>, and the auditor's central task is to confirm that adequate controls were identified early and built in, not retrofitted after problems appear. The exam expects fluency in the control taxonomies and, above all, in <span class='keyterm'>application controls</span> — the input, processing, and output controls that ensure data is complete, accurate, valid, authorized, and auditable.</p><h3>Control Categories: Function and Nature</h3><p>By <em>function</em>, controls are <span class='keyterm'>preventive</span> (stop an error or unauthorized act before it happens — e.g., input validation, access controls, segregation of duties), <span class='keyterm'>detective</span> (identify that something has gone wrong — e.g., reconciliations, exception reports, audit logs, hash totals), or <span class='keyterm'>corrective</span> (fix the problem and restore correct state — e.g., error-correction routines, backups and recovery, business continuity). Preventive controls are generally preferred where feasible because stopping an error is cheaper than detecting and correcting it, but a layered combination of all three (<span class='keyterm'>defense in depth</span>) is the robust design. A second axis distinguishes <span class='keyterm'>general controls</span> — pervasive IT controls over the environment (change management, access management, operations, physical security) that apply across all applications — from <span class='keyterm'>application controls</span>, which are specific to a single application's transactions. If the general control environment is weak (for instance, poor change management), the auditor cannot rely on application controls, because they could be altered without detection. This dependency is a frequent exam point.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Preventive</td><td>Stop the event before it occurs</td><td>Edit/validation checks, access control, SoD, well-designed forms</td></tr><tr><td>Detective</td><td>Discover the event after it occurs</td><td>Reconciliations, exception/error reports, audit trails, hash totals</td></tr><tr><td>Corrective</td><td>Remedy and restore correct state</td><td>Error correction, backup/recovery, incident response</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Application Controls: Input</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Input controls</span> ensure that data entering the system is authorized, complete, accurate, and valid — \"garbage in, garbage out\" is prevented here. The exam expects you to recognize specific edit and validation checks:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Check digit</span> — an extra digit computed from the others (e.g., in an account number) that detects transcription and transposition errors when a key value is entered.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Validity check</span> — the value must belong to a valid set (a state code that exists; a status that is one of the allowed codes).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Range / limit / reasonableness check</span> — the value must fall within acceptable bounds (an age between 0 and 120; an hourly wage under a sane maximum).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Completeness / mandatory-field check</span> — required fields are present and not blank.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Existence / table look-up check</span> — the code matches an entry in a reference table (a product code that exists in the catalog).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Key verification</span> — critical data is entered twice by two people and compared, catching keystroke errors.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Sequence check</span> — records or documents arrive in expected order with no gaps, detecting missing or duplicate items.</li></ul><p>At the batch level, <span class='keyterm'>batch controls</span> verify that a group of transactions was processed completely and accurately. A <span class='keyterm'>record count</span> confirms the number of records; a <span class='keyterm'>financial (control) total</span> sums a money field; and a <span class='keyterm'>hash total</span> sums an otherwise meaningless field (like account numbers) purely to detect change — a hash total has no business meaning, and recognizing that distinction is a classic exam item. Batch totals computed before input are reconciled to totals after processing to prove nothing was lost, added, or altered.</p><p>Input controls also govern <em>authorization</em>, not just accuracy. Source documents and transactions should be authorized before entry, and the system should enforce that only permitted users can initiate particular transaction types — an application-level expression of segregation of duties. For online entry, controls such as pre-numbered transactions, screen-level edit checks that reject bad input at the point of entry, and forced completion of mandatory fields catch errors before they enter processing, which is far cheaper than detecting them downstream. The design principle the auditor endorses is to <em>reject or flag errors as early as possible and as close to the source as possible</em>, because an error caught at data entry can be corrected by the person who has the context to fix it, whereas one caught three processing steps later is expensive to trace and correct. Error handling itself is a control: rejected transactions should go to a controlled <span class='keyterm'>suspense/error file</span>, be corrected and re-entered through the same edit controls (not bypassing them), and be tracked so that none is simply lost. An error file that grows without being cleared is a red flag the auditor looks for.</p><p>A useful way to organize all of this is by the <span class='keyterm'>control objectives</span> the controls serve: <em>completeness</em> (every valid transaction is processed once and only once — served by record counts, sequence checks, run-to-run totals), <em>accuracy</em> (data values are correct — served by validation, check digits, reasonableness checks), <em>validity/authorization</em> (only genuine, authorized transactions are processed — served by access controls, approvals, existence checks), and <em>maintenance of the audit trail</em> (events can be reconstructed — served by transaction logging). When the exam asks what a specific control <em>achieves</em>, mapping it to one of these objectives usually points to the right answer: a hash total serves completeness, a check digit serves accuracy, an approval serves validity, and a transaction log serves auditability.</p><h3>Application Controls: Processing</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Processing controls</span> ensure data is processed completely and accurately once inside the system and that files are updated correctly. They include <span class='keyterm'>run-to-run totals</span> (carrying control totals from one processing stage to the next and reconciling at each step so any loss is localized), <span class='keyterm'>edit checks during processing</span>, <span class='keyterm'>reasonableness and limit checks</span> on calculated results, and <span class='keyterm'>reconciliation</span> of file totals before and after updates. <span class='keyterm'>Concurrency controls</span> prevent two simultaneous updates from corrupting a record. Underlying many of these is the requirement that the system maintain a complete <span class='keyterm'>audit trail (transaction log)</span> — a chronological record of transactions and changes with enough detail (who, what, when, before/after values) to reconstruct events and support both detective control and investigation. The auditor treats a robust, tamper-resistant audit trail as one of the most important controls to verify, because so much detective and corrective capability depends on it.</p><h3>Application Controls: Output</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Output controls</span> ensure that results are complete, accurate, and distributed only to authorized recipients. They include reconciliation of output totals back to input and processing control totals, review of output for reasonableness, controlled and logged distribution of sensitive reports, secure handling and retention of output, and error/exception reports that are actually followed up and cleared. Negotiable or sensitive output (checks, statements) demands additional custody and reconciliation controls. The auditor confirms not merely that reports are produced but that someone with the right authority reviews exception reports and that the loop is closed — an unmonitored exception report is not a functioning detective control.</p><p>A theme that ties input, processing, and output together is <span class='keyterm'>end-to-end reconciliation</span>: control totals established at input are carried forward and reconciled at each processing stage and again at output, so that if the numbers stop balancing, the break can be localized to a specific step rather than hunted for across the whole flow. This is why hash totals, record counts, and financial control totals are computed early and re-checked repeatedly rather than only once. For online and real-time systems, where there is no natural batch, the equivalent controls are per-transaction validation at entry, immediate logging to an audit trail, and periodic reconciliation of the application's data against independent sources or control accounts. Whatever the processing mode, the auditor's test is the same: can the organization demonstrate that what went in is what came out, with every exception accounted for and every change logged.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Two distinctions are heavily tested. First, a <b>hash total</b> is the sum of a field with <b>no intrinsic meaning</b> (e.g., account numbers), used purely to detect completeness/alteration — contrast it with a financial total, which sums a meaningful money field. Second, know the <b>function categories</b>: reconciliations, logs, and exception reports are <b>detective</b>; input validation and access controls are <b>preventive</b>; backups and error-correction are <b>corrective</b>.</p></div><h3>Segregation of Duties and Where Controls Are Designed</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Segregation of duties (SoD)</span> — ensuring no single individual controls a transaction end to end (for example, initiate, approve, record, and reconcile) — is a preventive control that must be reflected in the application's role and authorization design. In development itself, SoD means separating those who write code, those who test it, and those who move it to production, and keeping the <span class='keyterm'>development, test, and production environments</span> distinct (see Section 6). Where automated SoD cannot be fully achieved (common in small organizations), the auditor looks for <span class='keyterm'>compensating controls</span> such as supervisory review, reconciliations by an independent party, and detailed audit-log review. The overriding message of this section for the exam: the auditor's <b>preferred</b> answer is almost always to <em>build the control into the system design</em> and to confirm control requirements were specified during requirements/design — because a control designed in early is cheaper, stronger, and less likely to be bypassed than one added after go-live.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>During design review of a new payments application, the auditor notes that account numbers are keyed manually and that no edit check is specified for them. The <b>best</b> recommendation is to add a <b>check digit</b> on the account number to catch transcription/transposition errors at input, complemented by an existence check against the customer master and a batch <b>hash total</b> on account numbers to confirm completeness through processing — designing these controls in now, during design, rather than relying on downstream detection after erroneous payments have already been made.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"System Readiness and Implementation Testing","body":"<p>Testing is where the auditor gains assurance that the system does what the requirements said it should — completely, accurately, and securely — before it touches real business. The exam's recurring themes are: know the <em>levels</em> of testing and what each proves; know that <span class='keyterm'>user acceptance testing (UAT)</span> is owned by the business, not IT; understand test data and environment controls; and recognize that <span class='keyterm'>regression testing</span> guards against a fix or enhancement breaking something that previously worked. The auditor evaluates whether a documented <span class='keyterm'>test plan</span> exists, whether tests trace back to requirements, whether results are documented and defects tracked to closure, and whether formal sign-off precedes go-live.</p><h3>The Levels of Testing</h3><p>Testing proceeds from the smallest unit outward, each level proving something the previous could not:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Unit testing</span> — tests an individual program or module in isolation, usually by the developer, to confirm the smallest piece of logic works.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Integration (interface) testing</span> — tests that modules and components work correctly <em>together</em> and that data passes correctly across interfaces; it exposes faults that unit tests, by design, cannot see.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>System testing</span> — tests the complete, integrated system against its functional and non-functional requirements (performance, security, usability, recovery) in a full test environment.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>User acceptance testing (UAT)</span> — the <em>business users</em> validate that the system meets their requirements and is fit for purpose, against acceptance criteria the users defined. UAT ownership by users is a heavily tested point: developers cannot sign off their own acceptance. Formal user sign-off from UAT is the key gate before production, and the auditor looks for it as evidence.</li></ul><p>Two special variants matter. <span class='keyterm'>Regression testing</span> re-runs previously passed tests after a change to confirm existing functionality still works — the antidote to \"we fixed one thing and broke another,\" and essential wherever code is modified. <span class='keyterm'>Sociability testing</span> confirms the new system can operate in its target environment <em>alongside</em> other existing systems without adversely affecting them — an important but often overlooked check when a new application shares infrastructure with production workloads.</p><p>Two further distinctions round out the vocabulary. Testing can proceed <span class='keyterm'>bottom-up</span> — starting with the lowest-level modules and combining upward, which requires <em>drivers</em> to simulate the higher-level callers that do not yet exist — or <span class='keyterm'>top-down</span> — starting with the high-level control structure and working down, which requires <em>stubs</em> to stand in for lower modules not yet built. Bottom-up gives early confidence in core functions but delays a working whole; top-down gives an early skeletal system for user feedback but leaves detailed logic tested late. The auditor need not prescribe either but should confirm that whichever approach is used, integration faults are actually exercised. Separately, <span class='keyterm'>alpha and beta testing</span> describe who tests a product before general release: alpha testing is internal, by the organization's own staff, while beta testing puts a near-final version in the hands of a limited set of real external users to surface issues under real conditions before full rollout.</p><p>Underlying all levels is <span class='keyterm'>requirements traceability</span>: each requirement — functional, non-functional, and control — should map to one or more test cases, so that the test set demonstrably covers what the system was contracted to do. The auditor uses a traceability matrix to answer the pointed question, \"which test proves that this control requirement was met?\" A requirement with no corresponding test is an untested promise. This is why the auditor is especially interested in whether the <em>control and security requirements</em> identified in Section 4 have explicit test cases: it is common for functional features to be thoroughly tested while the input-validation, audit-trail, and access controls that the auditor most cares about are exercised only incidentally, if at all. Confirming deliberate, evidenced testing of controls — including negative test cases that deliberately submit invalid, out-of-range, and unauthorized inputs to prove the controls reject them — is one of the highest-value checks the auditor performs on a testing program.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Test level</th><th>What it proves</th><th>Typically performed by</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Unit</td><td>A single module's internal logic is correct</td><td>Developer</td></tr><tr><td>Integration / interface</td><td>Modules and interfaces work together; data passes correctly</td><td>Development / QA</td></tr><tr><td>System</td><td>The whole system meets functional and non-functional requirements</td><td>QA / test team</td></tr><tr><td>User acceptance (UAT)</td><td>The system is fit for business purpose vs. user criteria</td><td>Business users (owns sign-off)</td></tr><tr><td>Regression</td><td>A change did not break previously working function</td><td>QA (after every change)</td></tr><tr><td>Sociability</td><td>New system coexists with existing systems safely</td><td>QA / operations</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Test Approaches: White Box, Black Box, and Techniques</h3><p>The exam distinguishes test <em>approaches</em>. <span class='keyterm'>White-box (structural) testing</span> is based on knowledge of the internal code and logic paths; the tester designs cases to exercise specific branches, conditions, and paths, aiming for logic coverage. It is well suited to unit-level testing by those who can see the code. <span class='keyterm'>Black-box (functional) testing</span> ignores internal structure and tests inputs against expected outputs based purely on the specification; it is well suited to system and acceptance testing and to independent testers who validate behavior, not implementation. A robust program uses both: white box to prove the code's internal logic, black box to prove it meets the requirements. Other useful techniques include <span class='keyterm'>stress/load and performance testing</span> (behavior under peak and beyond-peak volume), <span class='keyterm'>recovery testing</span> (correct restoration after a failure), and <span class='keyterm'>security/penetration testing</span> (resistance to abuse). The auditor's concern is coverage: were the important requirements — especially the control and security requirements — actually exercised, and is there evidence of the results?</p><h3>Test Data, Environments, and Controls</h3><p>Sound testing depends on realistic yet safe data and on controlled environments. Test cases should cover not only valid \"happy path\" inputs but <em>invalid, boundary, and exception conditions</em> — the auditor is often more interested in whether the system correctly rejects and handles bad data than in whether it processes good data, because that is where controls prove themselves. A frequent audit concern is the use of <span class='keyterm'>live production data in test</span>: copying real customer or financial data into a less-protected test environment can breach privacy and confidentiality obligations. The preferred controls are to use <em>sanitized, masked, or synthetically generated</em> test data, or, if production data is genuinely required for fidelity, to apply the same protections to the test environment and obtain proper authorization. The <span class='keyterm'>test environment should mirror production</span> as closely as feasible so results are meaningful, yet remain <em>separate</em> from production so testing cannot corrupt live data or processing. Test results, defect logs, and re-test evidence should be retained; defects should be risk-rated, tracked, and either resolved or formally accepted before go-live.</p><p>CISA also expects awareness of audit techniques that reuse testing concepts. <span class='keyterm'>Test data / test decks</span> let the auditor push known transactions through the live program and compare actual to expected output to verify processing controls. An <span class='keyterm'>integrated test facility (ITF)</span> embeds a fictitious dummy entity in the production system so test transactions can be processed alongside real ones (results must be reversed/excluded from real totals). <span class='keyterm'>Parallel simulation</span> reprocesses real production data through an independent, auditor-controlled program and compares results. These are auditor tools, but the same discipline — known inputs, expected outputs, controlled environment — underlies good development testing.</p><p>The auditor evaluates a testing program along several axes beyond mere execution. First, <em>independence</em>: unit testing by the developer is expected, but higher levels — especially system and acceptance testing — carry more weight when performed by people other than those who wrote the code, because authors are poor detectors of their own blind spots. A quality-assurance function separate from development is the structural expression of this. Second, <em>completeness of evidence</em>: a defensible program produces a documented test plan, individual test cases with expected results, records of actual results, a defect log that tracks each issue through to resolution or formal acceptance, and evidence of re-testing after fixes. \"We tested it and it worked\" without artifacts is not auditable assurance. Third, <em>defect management discipline</em>: open defects should be risk-rated, and the decision to go live with any unresolved defect should be an explicit, authorized acceptance of that risk by the business, not a silent omission. Fourth, <em>coverage of the negative and the exceptional</em>: because controls exist precisely to handle bad input and abnormal conditions, a program that tests only valid transactions leaves the very controls the auditor cares about unproven. Finally, the auditor confirms that the results actually gated the decision to proceed — that formal sign-off (functional sign-off from QA and, decisively, user sign-off from UAT) preceded promotion to production rather than following it as a formality after the system was already live.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><b>Who owns UAT?</b> The <b>business users</b> — and their formal sign-off is the gate to production. <b>White box</b> = internal code/logic knowledge (structural); <b>black box</b> = specification-based, no code knowledge (functional). If a change was made and the concern is unintended side effects, the control is <b>regression testing</b>. If real customer data is copied into test, the concern is <b>confidentiality/privacy</b> — recommend masking or synthetic data.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor finds that a critical billing system passed unit and system testing and went live, but users never performed acceptance testing and provided no sign-off; shortly after go-live, users reported the system did not support a required billing scenario. The auditor's finding is that the <b>absence of user acceptance testing and formal user sign-off</b> allowed a system that did not meet business requirements to reach production. The recommendation is to require documented UAT against user-defined acceptance criteria, with business sign-off as a mandatory gate before any future implementation.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Implementation Configuration and Release Management","body":"<p>Once code passes testing, moving it into production must itself be controlled. Two disciplines govern this: <span class='keyterm'>configuration management</span>, which keeps authoritative track of every component and version that makes up the system, and <span class='keyterm'>release (change and deployment) management</span>, which governs how approved changes are promoted into production. For the IS auditor these are among the most important general controls in all of IT, because if changes can reach production without authorization, testing, and a record, then <em>no</em> other control — including all the application controls of Section 4 — can be relied upon, since it could have been altered silently.</p><h3>Configuration Management and Version Control</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Configuration management (CM)</span> identifies and records all <span class='keyterm'>configuration items (CIs)</span> — programs, modules, libraries, scripts, parameters, documentation — and their versions and relationships, typically in a <span class='keyterm'>configuration management database (CMDB)</span> or repository. A <span class='keyterm'>baseline</span> is a formally reviewed, approved version that serves as a reference point; changes are made against baselines under control. <span class='keyterm'>Version control</span> systems record every change to source with who/what/when, enable rollback to a prior known-good version, and prevent the chaos of developers overwriting each other's work. The auditor verifies that the organization can answer, for any component in production, \"which version is running, who approved it, and when did it change,\" and can reproduce a prior release if needed. Weak configuration management shows up as \"we're not sure which version is in production,\" an answer that should alarm any auditor.</p><p>Configuration management underpins several other controls and is worth understanding as a foundation rather than a bookkeeping chore. Because it establishes the authoritative record of what <em>should</em> be in production, it enables the auditor and the organization to detect <span class='keyterm'>unauthorized change</span>: comparing the live environment against the approved baseline reveals any component that differs from what was formally approved, which is often the first sign of an undocumented emergency fix, a developer bypass, or even malicious tampering. It also enables reliable <span class='keyterm'>rollback</span> — you cannot restore a known-good prior version if you never recorded which version was good — and reliable incident diagnosis, since knowing exactly what changed and when narrows the search for a newly introduced fault. For packaged and infrastructure software, configuration management extends to tracking versions, patch levels, and configuration parameters, so the organization can answer whether a security patch has been applied everywhere it should be. The auditor's practical test is to pick a production component and ask the organization to produce its current version, its change history, and the approvals behind each change; an inability to do so is itself the finding.</p><h3>Change Management and Code Promotion</h3><p>A disciplined <span class='keyterm'>change management</span> process is the exam's centerpiece here. Every change — whether a bug fix, an enhancement, or a patch — should be <em>requested and documented, assessed for risk and impact, approved by an appropriate authority (often a change advisory board), tested, scheduled, implemented, and reviewed</em>, with the ability to <span class='keyterm'>back out (roll back)</span> if it fails. Crucial to control is that <span class='keyterm'>the developer does not move his or her own code into production</span>; promotion should be performed by a separate function (operations, release management, or an automated pipeline with independent approval), preserving segregation of duties. The classic path is a controlled <span class='keyterm'>code promotion / migration</span> through separated environments:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Environment</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Control emphasis</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Development</td><td>Coding and unit testing by developers</td><td>Developers have access; isolated from live data</td></tr><tr><td>Test / QA (and staging)</td><td>Integration, system, UAT; staging mirrors production</td><td>Independent testers; controlled test data</td></tr><tr><td>Production</td><td>Live operation serving the business</td><td>Developers have NO change access; changes only via approved release</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Keeping <span class='keyterm'>development, test, and production strictly separate</span> — ideally on different infrastructure with different access — is a fundamental control. Developers must not have standing write access to production, and production data must not flow freely back into development. The auditor tests change management by <em>sampling recent production changes and tracing each back to an authorized, tested, approved request</em>; a change in production with no matching approved record is a serious finding. The auditor also confirms that back-out plans exist and that changes are reviewed after implementation.</p><p>Several finer points recur on the exam. Authorization should come from someone <em>independent of the person who developed the change</em> and be based on an assessment of the change's risk and business impact — trivial, low-risk changes may follow a lighter (\"standard\" or pre-approved) path, while high-risk changes demand fuller scrutiny by a <span class='keyterm'>change advisory board (CAB)</span>. Testing evidence should exist <em>before</em> approval to deploy, not after. Changes should be <span class='keyterm'>scheduled</span> to minimize business disruption (maintenance windows) and communicated to affected users. And crucially, the person who <em>moves</em> the code and the person who <em>wrote</em> it should not be the same, so that the act of promotion is an independent control point rather than a self-service action. Where full separation of individuals is impractical in a small shop, the compensating control is independent after-the-fact review of every migration against its authorization. The auditor also watches for the subtle risk that test and production drift apart over time — if the environment code is tested in differs materially from production, a change that passed testing can still fail live, which is why staging environments are kept as faithful to production as possible.</p><h3>Emergency Changes and Patch Management</h3><p>Not every change can wait for the full cycle. <span class='keyterm'>Emergency changes</span> (to fix a production outage or urgent security hole) are legitimately expedited, but the exam expects the compensating discipline: emergency changes still require <em>after-the-fact documentation, review, and formal approval</em>, and any temporary elevated access (e.g., a developer given short-term production access via a break-glass/firecall ID) must be time-limited, logged, and reviewed. The risk the auditor watches for is emergency procedures becoming the routine bypass around normal controls. <span class='keyterm'>Patch management</span> is a specialized change process for applying vendor security and functionality updates: patches should be assessed for applicability and risk, tested in a non-production environment where practical, deployed on a risk-based schedule, and tracked so the organization can prove its systems are current. Unpatched systems and untested patches that break production are both common findings.</p><h3>Release Management and Automation</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Release management</span> bundles related changes into a controlled release, coordinates its build, testing, and deployment, and communicates it to stakeholders. In modern <span class='keyterm'>CI/CD</span> pipelines much of this is automated, which improves consistency and speed but shifts the control questions rather than removing them: the auditor now examines whether the pipeline enforces mandatory peer review, automated test and security gates, and an independent approval before production promotion; whether segregation of duties survives (a developer should not be able to both write and unilaterally deploy without an independent gate); and whether the pipeline's logs form a complete, tamper-resistant audit trail of what was built, tested, approved, and released. Automation is a control opportunity when the gates are enforced and evidenced — and a control risk when it lets code flow to production with no independent checkpoint.</p><p>It helps to see how the pieces fit into one coherent control system. Configuration management provides the <em>record</em> of what exists and what is approved; change management provides the <em>process</em> by which that record is allowed to change; release management provides the <em>coordination</em> of packaging and deploying approved changes; and environment segregation provides the <em>structural separation</em> that keeps the people and systems apart at each stage. Remove any one and the others weaken: perfect change approvals are worthless if the wrong version can still be deployed (a configuration failure), and perfect version tracking is worthless if anyone can push a change without approval (a change-management failure). This is why the auditor examines them together and why a weakness in this area is so consequential — it is the general-control foundation on which reliance on <em>all</em> application controls ultimately rests. If a determined developer can alter production silently, then the check digits, reconciliations, and audit trails of Section 4 could have been quietly weakened or removed, and the auditor cannot place assurance on any of them.</p><p>Concretely, the auditor's tests in this area are among the most reliable in the whole domain because they produce hard evidence. Trace a sample of production changes to authorized, tested, approved requests; compare the running production configuration against the approved baseline to detect unauthorized change; review the list of who holds production access and confirm developers are not on it (or, if they are for support reasons, that the access is controlled, monitored, and justified); inspect emergency-change records for after-the-fact approval; and examine the change and deployment logs for completeness and integrity. Findings here — an unapproved change, an unexplained configuration difference, standing developer access to production — are difficult for management to dispute and directly undermine confidence in the system as a whole.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>The single most tested control here: <b>developers must not migrate their own code to production</b>, and dev/test/prod must be <b>segregated</b>. To test change management, the auditor <b>samples production changes and traces each to an approved, tested request</b>. Emergency changes are allowed but must be <b>documented and approved after the fact</b>; break-glass access must be temporary and reviewed.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>Reviewing change management, an auditor selects 25 recent production changes and finds 3 with no change request, no evidence of testing, and no approval — implemented directly by a developer who has standing production access. The <b>greatest</b> concern is the combination of <b>unauthorized, untested changes and developer access to production</b>, which defeats segregation of duties and undermines reliance on every application control. The recommendation is to remove developers' standing production access, route all changes through an approval-and-test workflow with an independent promotion step, and reconcile production against the authorized baseline.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"System Migration, Infrastructure Deployment, and Data Conversion","body":"<p>Cutting over from an old system to a new one is one of the highest-risk moments in the whole life cycle, and it is a rich source of exam questions. Three intertwined activities dominate: choosing a <span class='keyterm'>changeover (conversion) strategy</span>, deploying the supporting <span class='keyterm'>infrastructure</span>, and performing <span class='keyterm'>data conversion/migration</span>. The auditor's core concerns are that <em>data moves completely and accurately with its integrity intact</em>, that a <em>tested fallback</em> exists if the cutover fails, and that the strategy chosen fits the organization's risk tolerance.</p><h3>Changeover Strategies Compared</h3><p>The four canonical changeover strategies trade risk against cost and effort, and the exam expects you to match a scenario to the right one:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Parallel changeover</span> — old and new systems run <em>simultaneously</em> for a period, and their outputs are compared. This is the <em>lowest-risk</em> option because the old system remains a working fallback and discrepancies reveal conversion errors, but it is the most costly and labor-intensive (two systems, double data entry). Favored for critical systems where failure is intolerable.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Phased (gradual) changeover</span> — the new system is introduced in stages (by module, location, or function), limiting exposure at each step and allowing lessons to carry forward. It reduces risk relative to a single big cutover but prolongs the transition and can require temporary interfaces between old and new during the overlap.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Pilot changeover</span> — the new system goes live for a <em>limited group</em> (one site or department) first; if it succeeds there, it is rolled out more widely. It contains the blast radius of failure to a small population.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Direct cutover (big-bang / abrupt)</span> — the old system is switched off and the new one switched on at a single point in time. This is the <em>fastest and cheapest</em> but <em>highest-risk</em> approach, because there is no parallel fallback; if the new system fails, recovery depends entirely on backups and a rehearsed rollback plan. The auditor's central question for a direct cutover is whether a <b>tested back-out/fallback plan</b> exists.</li></ul><table><thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Risk</th><th>Cost/effort</th><th>Fallback</th><th>Best when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Parallel</td><td>Lowest</td><td>Highest</td><td>Old system stays live</td><td>Critical systems; failure intolerable</td></tr><tr><td>Phased</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Moderate, prolonged</td><td>Unconverted parts remain on old</td><td>Large systems divisible into stages</td></tr><tr><td>Pilot</td><td>Contained</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Only pilot group exposed</td><td>Many similar sites; test before wide rollout</td></tr><tr><td>Direct (big-bang)</td><td>Highest</td><td>Lowest</td><td>Backups/rollback only</td><td>Small/low-risk; parallel impractical</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Data Conversion and Migration Risks and Controls</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Data conversion</span> — extracting data from the legacy system, transforming it to the new system's format, and loading it (ETL) — is where integrity is most at risk. The threats are that records are <em>lost</em>, <em>duplicated</em>, <em>truncated</em>, <em>mis-mapped</em> to the wrong fields, or corrupted by encoding and format mismatches; legacy data may also be dirty (incomplete, inconsistent), and converting bad data merely carries the problem forward. The controls the auditor expects to see are quantitative and verifiable:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Reconciliation of record counts and control totals</span> before and after migration — the number of records and the sums of key financial and quantity fields in the source must equal those in the target, proving completeness and that nothing was silently dropped or added.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Data validation and integrity checks</span> on the loaded data — referential integrity, valid values, and field-level checks confirm accuracy, not just count.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Data cleansing before conversion</span> — identifying and correcting dirty data first, rather than importing errors.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Sampling and comparison</span> — tracing a sample of records end-to-end from old to new to confirm correct mapping and values.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>A tested rollback / fallback</span> — a verified backup of source data and a rehearsed plan to revert if conversion fails, so the organization is never stranded between two systems.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Formal user sign-off on converted data</span> — the business confirms the migrated data is correct and complete before the new system is trusted.</li></ul><p>The exam repeatedly frames the auditor's <b>primary</b> concern in a migration as <em>data integrity</em> — completeness and accuracy of the converted data — verified through reconciliation of totals between source and target. A \"successful\" cutover with unreconciled data is not a success; it is a hidden liability.</p><p>The mechanics of a controlled conversion are worth spelling out because the exam tests them obliquely. Before conversion, the source data should be <em>profiled and cleansed</em> so that known defects are corrected or explicitly accepted rather than silently migrated. The transformation logic — the mapping of each source field to its target field, including any recoding of values or restructuring of relationships — should be documented and reviewed, because a wrong mapping can load data that reconciles on totals yet is semantically corrupt (for example, mapping an amount into the wrong currency field). The load should ideally be <em>rehearsed</em> in a non-production run using a full copy of the data, both to validate the process and to measure how long the cutover window must be. After the load, reconciliation is performed at multiple levels: overall record counts, control totals on key financial and quantity fields, and targeted sampling that traces individual records end to end. Any records that fail to convert must be captured on an <span class='keyterm'>error/exception report</span>, investigated, and resolved — not quietly dropped, which is a classic way for the counts to \"balance\" only because the failures were discarded. The auditor treats the conversion's exception handling as carefully as its success path, because that is where completeness silently leaks away.</p><p>Auditor involvement in a conversion can be preventive or detective. Preventively, the auditor reviews the conversion plan and controls before cutover and may recommend improvements while there is still time to act. Detectively, after conversion, the auditor independently reconciles source to target — sometimes re-performing the count and total comparisons using their own scripts rather than relying on the project team's figures — and reviews the exception reports and their disposition. Because a botched conversion can corrupt the integrity of every downstream report and control, the auditor's judgment is that conversion assurance is not optional even when the timeline is tight; if reconciliation and a tested fallback are not in place, the correct recommendation is to <em>delay go-live</em> rather than accept unverified data into production.</p><h3>Infrastructure Deployment Readiness</h3><p>Beyond software and data, the new system needs its <span class='keyterm'>infrastructure</span> — servers, storage, network, security controls, and interfaces — provisioned, configured, hardened, and tested. The auditor checks that infrastructure was <span class='keyterm'>configured to a secure baseline</span> (hardening standards applied, default credentials changed, unnecessary services disabled), that capacity and performance were validated under expected load, that <span class='keyterm'>backup and recovery</span> and, for important systems, <span class='keyterm'>business continuity/disaster recovery</span> provisions are in place before go-live rather than after, and that interfaces to surrounding systems were tested (sociability). A go-live that outruns its infrastructure readiness — unhardened servers, no backups yet, untested capacity — is a common and serious finding. A documented, approved <span class='keyterm'>implementation (cutover) plan</span> with a go/no-go decision, defined roles, a communication plan, and explicit fallback criteria ties all of this together, and the auditor treats the existence and quality of that plan as key evidence of readiness.</p><p>The <span class='keyterm'>go/no-go decision</span> deserves particular attention as a control in its own right. A disciplined cutover defines, in advance, the objective criteria that must be met to proceed — data reconciled and signed off, testing complete with no unacceptable open defects, infrastructure hardened and backed up, fallback plan tested, support and operations ready, users trained — and names the authority (typically the sponsor or steering committee) who makes the call against those criteria at a defined checkpoint. This prevents the all-too-common failure in which a project proceeds to go-live simply because the date arrived, regardless of whether it was actually ready. The auditor looks for evidence that the go/no-go was a genuine decision informed by readiness criteria, not a foregone conclusion. Equally important is the <span class='keyterm'>point of no return</span>: the plan should identify the moment beyond which rollback becomes impractical, and the criteria for invoking the fallback must be decided before that moment, not improvised during a crisis when judgment is worst.</p><p>Training and user readiness round out deployment. A technically flawless cutover still fails operationally if users do not know how to use the new system or if support staff cannot handle the surge of questions that follows any go-live. The auditor confirms that training was delivered, that documentation and procedures are available, that a support model (help desk, escalation, and often a period of heightened \"hypercare\" support) is in place, and that operations can run and recover the system. Readiness, in the auditor's view, is never only about the software and data — it is about the whole sociotechnical system being prepared to operate reliably from day one, with a rehearsed way back if it is not.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><b>Parallel = lowest risk (highest cost); direct/big-bang = highest risk (lowest cost).</b> For a critical system where failure is unacceptable, favor <b>parallel</b>. For any cutover — especially direct — the auditor's key question is whether a <b>tested fallback/back-out plan</b> exists. In data migration the <b>primary</b> concern is <b>data integrity</b>, verified by <b>reconciling record counts and control totals</b> between source and target.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An organization plans a direct cutover of its general ledger over a single weekend and intends to verify results \"by spot-checking a few screens\" after go-live. The auditor's <b>most important</b> recommendations are to establish <b>reconciliation of record counts and financial control totals</b> between the legacy and new ledgers to prove the conversion is complete and accurate, and to ensure a <b>tested backup and rollback plan</b> exists so the organization can revert if the cutover fails — because a direct cutover offers no parallel fallback and spot-checking screens cannot demonstrate data integrity.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Post-Implementation Review","body":"<p>The life cycle does not end at go-live. A <span class='keyterm'>post-implementation review (PIR)</span> — conducted after the system has been in production long enough to be exercised in real conditions, commonly a few months — closes the loop by asking whether the project actually delivered what it promised. For the IS auditor the PIR is both a governance control the organization should perform and, frequently, an engagement the auditor participates in or evaluates. Its purpose is to determine whether the system <em>met its objectives and business case</em>, whether the <em>controls are operating effectively in production</em>, whether the <em>projected benefits are being realized</em>, and what <em>lessons</em> should improve future projects.</p><h3>What the Post-Implementation Review Evaluates</h3><p>A thorough PIR examines several dimensions, and the exam expects you to recognize each:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Achievement of objectives and requirements</span> — does the delivered system meet the requirements and the goals set out in the business case? Are users able to do what the system was built to enable?</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Benefits realization</span> — comparing <em>actual</em> benefits against those projected in the business case (the anticipated cost savings, efficiency gains, revenue). This is where the promises made to justify the investment are finally tested against reality, and it is one of the PIR's most important functions.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Cost and schedule performance</span> — did the project deliver within its approved budget and timeline, and if not, why? These variances inform future estimating.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Control effectiveness</span> — are the application and general controls designed in Section 4 actually operating as intended now that real transactions flow through them? The auditor looks for exceptions, error rates, and whether reconciliations and audit trails work in practice.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>User satisfaction and adoption</span> — are users actually using the system as intended, and are operational and support processes coping?</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Problems, defects, and lessons learned</span> — what went wrong (in the product and in the project), what workarounds are in place, and what should be done differently next time. Lessons learned feed back into the organization's methodology, closing the improvement loop.</li></ul><p>It is worth separating <em>product</em> questions from <em>process</em> questions, because the PIR answers both and the exam sometimes tests the distinction. The product questions ask whether the delivered system is right: does it meet requirements, do its controls work, are its benefits real, is it performant and reliable in production. The process questions ask whether the project that produced it was well run: was it on budget and schedule, was scope controlled, was the methodology followed, did governance function. A system can succeed as a product even though the project overran (a good outcome delivered painfully), or a project can hit every deadline and budget yet deliver a product that fails to realize its benefits (an on-time delivery of the wrong thing). The auditor keeps these threads separate so that a superficially \"successful\" go-live does not mask a failure to deliver value, and so that lessons about project execution are captured even when the product is sound.</p><h3>Verifying Controls Operate in Production</h3><p>The PIR is the first chance to confirm that the controls designed during Section 4 actually function against real transactions and real users rather than test data. A control can pass system testing yet fail in production because live volumes, real edge cases, or user workarounds expose gaps that neat test cases never triggered. The auditor therefore examines production evidence directly: are edit and validation checks actually rejecting the bad input they were meant to catch, or have users found ways around them; are reconciliations and run-to-run totals being performed and balancing, or are imbalances being ignored; are exception and error reports being generated <em>and acted upon</em>, or are they piling up unreviewed; is the audit trail complete and tamper-resistant, capturing who did what and when. The auditor also confirms that segregation of duties survived contact with production — that emergency-access and temporary-privilege routes used during the stabilization period were closed and reviewed, and that developers do not retain the standing production access they may have been granted to firefight go-live issues. Finding that a well-designed control was quietly disabled or bypassed under go-live pressure is one of the most valuable outcomes a PIR can produce, because such gaps rarely surface any other way.</p><table><thead><tr><th>PIR question</th><th>Evidence the auditor seeks</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Did it meet objectives / requirements?</td><td>Requirements traceability, user confirmation, defect rates</td></tr><tr><td>Were projected benefits realized?</td><td>Baseline vs. actual metrics; owner accountable for benefits</td></tr><tr><td>On budget and schedule?</td><td>Actual vs. approved cost and timeline; variance analysis</td></tr><tr><td>Are controls effective in production?</td><td>Exception/error reports, reconciliations, audit-log review</td></tr><tr><td>What are the lessons learned?</td><td>Documented review, fed into future project methodology</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Timing, Independence, and Method</h3><p>Timing matters: a PIR held too soon captures only teething problems, while one held too late lets issues fester and benefits go unmeasured. The convention is to allow the system to run through enough real business cycles (often three to six months) that steady-state behavior and actual benefits can be observed. <span class='keyterm'>Independence</span> also matters: the review is more credible when conducted or validated by parties who were not solely responsible for building the system — which is why IS auditors are natural participants, provided they preserved their objectivity during development (advising on controls is fine; making design decisions is not). The method combines evidence: metrics against the business-case baseline, user interviews and surveys, examination of production error and exception data, and review of the operating controls. The auditor's deliverable is an objective assessment of whether value was delivered and controls work — not a celebration of go-live.</p><h3>Why the PIR Matters to Governance</h3><p>Without a PIR, an organization never learns whether its IT investments pay off; it approves projects on projected benefits and never checks. The PIR enforces <span class='keyterm'>accountability</span> — the sponsor who promised benefits is held to them — and drives <span class='keyterm'>continuous improvement</span> by feeding lessons into future estimating, methodology, and control design. A recurring exam theme is that discovering, during a PIR, that projected benefits were <em>not</em> realized is itself a valuable outcome: it triggers corrective action (tuning the system, changing processes, or reconsidering the investment) and improves the credibility of future business cases. The mature organization treats the PIR not as a formality but as the mechanism that keeps the entire acquire-develop-implement cycle honest.</p><p>The PIR should also produce a documented, actionable output rather than an unread report. Good practice is a review report that records the objectives-versus-outcomes assessment, the benefits-realization measurement against the baseline, control-effectiveness findings, and a list of lessons learned with owners and target dates for corrective action. Those corrective actions matter to the auditor as much as the findings: a benefit shortfall that is identified but never acted upon is only half a control. The report is presented to the sponsor and steering committee — the same governance bodies that approved the investment — so accountability comes full circle, and its lessons are fed into the organization's project methodology, estimating models, and standard control catalogue so that the next project starts from a higher baseline. In this way the PIR is the connective tissue that turns each project into organizational learning rather than a one-off effort whose insights evaporate when the team disbands.</p><p>Finally, the auditor is alert to the ways a PIR can be undermined. It can be skipped entirely because \"the system is live and everyone has moved on\" — the most common failure, and one that quietly forfeits any check on whether the money was well spent. It can be reduced to a self-assessment by the very team that built the system, which lacks the independence to report unwelcome findings. It can be timed too early, capturing only stabilization noise, or too late, after problems have hardened into accepted workarounds and benefits have gone unmeasured. And it can measure only what is easy — on-time, on-budget delivery — while ignoring the harder and more important questions of realized benefits and control effectiveness. When the auditor encounters any of these patterns, the recommendation is to institute a properly timed, independently validated PIR whose scope explicitly includes benefits realization and control operation, with results reported to governance and tracked to closure.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>The PIR's purpose is to confirm the system <b>met its objectives and business case, that controls work in production, and that projected benefits were realized</b> — and to capture <b>lessons learned</b>. Conduct it <b>after the system has run long enough</b> to observe real results, and ideally with <b>independent</b> involvement. If benefits were not realized, that finding is a feature of the PIR, not a failure of it — it drives corrective action.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>Six months after implementing a CRM system, management declares the project a success because it was delivered on time. Asked what the auditor should do <b>first</b>, the answer is to perform (or evaluate) a <b>post-implementation review</b> that measures <em>actual</em> outcomes against the <b>business case</b>: are the projected benefits (higher retention, faster service) being realized, are the built-in controls operating effectively on live data, and are users adopting the system? On-time delivery alone does not demonstrate that the investment delivered value — only comparison of actual results to the original objectives and benefits does.</p></div>"}];
